// Slow path: deduplicate concurrent refresh requests and propagate the result
func (ts *TokenSource) refresh() (*Token, error) {
    val, err, _ := ts.group.Do("refresh", func() (interface{}, error) {
        t, err := ts.upstream.FetchToken(context.Background())
        if err != nil {
            return nil, err
        }
        ts.mu.Lock()
        ts.cached = t
        ts.mu.Unlock()
        return t, nil
    })
    if err != nil {
        return nil, err
    }
    return val.(*Token), nil
}

## What Callers Receive When the Upstream Request Fails

Because all concurrent waiters share the single-flight result, an upstream error propagates to every caller waiting on that flight simultaneously, not just the goroutine that initiated the request. A transient auth service failure can therefore surface across many call sites at once. Callers should treat a Token() error as retriable at the call site rather than fatal.

We chose this over caching the last error and retrying on the next call because retrying on the next call would require callers to implement their own retry loops to get a token at all, and the failure mode would be harder to observe. The cost is that a single bad refresh can produce a burst of errors in calling code.

Errors from the upstream service are returned unwrapped. We chose this over wrapping in a sentinel error type because callers need to inspect the original status codes for retry decisions, and wrapping loses that fidelity unless every error type is explicitly re-exported. The tradeoff is that callers cannot distinguish a TokenSource coordination failure from an upstream auth failure using errors.Is or errors.As against a package-local type. If that distinction matters to your call site, file an issue; the error taxonomy is a known gap.

## How the Cache Behaves After a Failed Refresh

If a refresh fails, the cached token is not evicted. A caller that receives an error can call Token() again, and if the cached token has not crossed the hard expiry boundary — as opposed to the buffer — the fast path will return it. This behavior preserves availability during transient upstream outages at the cost of briefly issuing tokens closer to their expiry than the buffer intends.

We chose availability over strict buffer enforcement because the upstream auth service has historically shown correlated retry storms when clients simultaneously evict and re-request tokens after a partial outage.</draft>

