drafts.rubric:
Cache Invalidation: TTL Expiration and Mid-Session Revocation

Why These Two Paths Cannot Share a Single Eviction Mechanism

TTL expiration and explicit revocation look like the same operation from the outside — a cached token entry disappears — but they originate from opposite directions. TTL is the cache making a unilateral decision based on age. Revocation is an external system telling the cache that a previously valid entry is now wrong. Conflating them into a single eviction call was our first instinct, and it produced a subtle bug: a revoked token could survive until its TTL fired if the revocation message arrived during a write window. The paths are now kept strictly separate, and revocation always wins.

How TTL Expiration Works and What It Does Not Guarantee

We chose passive TTL expiration — relying on the store's native key expiry — over an active background sweeper that would poll and delete expired entries on a schedule. The active sweeper approach works and gives you precise control over when memory is reclaimed, but it introduces a second write path that races with your normal cache writers. The passive approach trades memory efficiency (expired keys linger until accessed or lazily swept) for the elimination of that race entirely. The tradeoff is worth stating plainly: a token whose TTL has technically elapsed may still occupy cache memory for a short window, but it will never be returned as valid because every read checks expiry before serving the entry.

The read-side expiry check is the hard guarantee. TTL is set at write time and is not renewed on access — we rejected sliding expiration because it allows a session that is continuously active to defer expiry indefinitely, which breaks the security invariant that tokens expire on a known schedule regardless of usage.

```
// Return cached token only if it has not yet expired
func getCachedToken(cache Store, key string, now time.Time) (*Token, bool) {
    entry, ok := cache.Get(key)
    if !ok {
        return nil, false
    }
    if now.After(entry.ExpiresAt) {
        cache.Delete(key)
        return nil, false
    }
    return entry.Token, true
}
```

The delete-on-read here is a courtesy eviction, not a correctness mechanism. Correctness is enforced by the expiry check above it.

How Explicit Revocation Reaches the Cache Before the TTL Does

When a token is revoked mid-session, the revocation event arrives through a separate channel — in our case, a pub/sub message from the auth service — and must invalidate the cache entry immediately, regardless of how much TTL remains. We chose push-based invalidation over a pull model where the cache would periodically re-validate entries against an authoritative revocation list. The pull model is viable and is simpler to reason about in isolation, but it introduces a revocation lag equal to your poll interval. For token revocation triggered by security events (credential compromise, forced logout), that lag is unacceptable.

The revocation handler acquires no application-level lock before deleting the entry. We debated a two-phase approach — mark as revoked, then sweep — but the marking phase creates a window where the entry is present and could be served if the expiry check runs between the mark and the sweep. A direct delete is atomic at the store level and closes that window. The cost is that if the delete message is lost in transit, the entry persists until TTL fires; see the section below on why that fallback is acceptable rather than a correctness gap.

```
// Remove a revoked token from the cache immediately on notification
func handleRevocation(cache Store, event RevocationEvent) {
    cache.Delete(event.TokenKey)
    metrics.RevocationLatency.Observe(time.Since(event.IssuedAt).Seconds())
}
```

The metrics call is outside the delete to avoid holding any internal store lock while recording — the revocation itself is already complete at that point.

When the Two Paths Meet: Revocation During a TTL Write Race

The dangerous interaction is a token that is being written to the cache at the same moment a revocation message arrives. If the write completes after the delete, the revoked token is back in the cache with a valid TTL. We handle this with a post-write revocation check: after any cache write, the writer immediately re-reads the revocation log (a lightweight in-memory bloom filter, not a network call) and deletes the entry it just wrote if the token appears there.

We chose the bloom filter check over holding a lock across the entire write-plus-revocation window because the lock approach either serializes all cache writes against all revocations (unacceptable throughput cost) or requires fine-grained per-token locking (complex and error-prone). The bloom filter admits false positives — a valid token may occasionally be evicted and force a re-fetch — but it admits no false negatives, meaning a revoked token will never survive the post-write check.

```
// Write a token to cache, then verify it has not been revoked since issuance
func writeWithRevocationCheck(cache Store, key string, t *Token, revoked *bloom.Filter) {
    entry := CacheEntry{Token: t, ExpiresAt: t.ExpiresAt}
    cache.Set(key, entry)
    if revoked.Test([]byte(t.ID)) {
        cache.Delete(key)
    }
}
```

The bloom filter is the only place the two invalidation paths explicitly touch. Everything else keeps them separate.

TTL as the Last Line of Defense, Not the First

A revocation message can be lost. The pub/sub broker can drop it; the cache node can be offline at the moment of delivery; the handler can panic before the delete completes. TTL expiration is the guarantee that even a missed revocation eventually resolves itself. This is why we chose TTL values that are meaningfully short — currently 15 minutes — over longer-lived entries that would reduce load on the token introspection endpoint. Longer TTLs would make the cache more efficient but would also extend the window during which a missed revocation leaves a compromised token usable. The 15-minute value is not arbitrary; it matches the maximum session drift we agreed to tolerate in the threat model.

Do not extend TTL values without revisiting that threat model discussion. The efficiency gain is real, but so is the exposure.

drafts.preference:
Cache Invalidation: Two Paths, One Source of Truth

Entries leave the cache in one of two ways: they expire naturally when their TTL elapses, or they get invalidated explicitly when something upstream changes — a token revocation being the clearest example. These paths look similar from the outside but behave differently internally, and conflating them causes subtle bugs.

TTL expiration is passive. The cache checks wall-clock time on read and discards stale entries without any coordination signal. Explicit invalidation is active — it writes a tombstone to the invalidation log before the entry would naturally expire, and any subsequent read checks that log first.

    func get(key string) (Entry, bool) {
        if tombstoned(key) {
            return Entry{}, false
        }
        e, ok := store[key]
        if !ok || time.Now().After(e.ExpiresAt) {
            return Entry{}, false
        }
        return e, true
    }

The tombstone check comes first. That ordering matters: a revoked token must not be served even if its TTL hasn't elapsed. We considered a single expiration mechanism for both cases — just setting TTL to zero on revocation — but that required cache writers to have write access during revocation events, which created an unacceptable coupling between the auth revocation path and the cache layer.

